{
  "article_id": "TheDawn1881",
  "paragraphs": [
    [
      {
        "text": "SAN NICOLAS ISLAND",
        "entity_key": "i_sn",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " is one of "
      },
      {
        "text": "a cluster",
        "entity_key": "i_chi",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " in the Bay of "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Barbara, California",
        "entity_key": "ci_sb",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ". Here for eighteen years lived the \""
      },
      {
        "text": "Lost Woman of San Nicolas",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ".\" The story of her life is a strange one. In 1835 "
      },
      {
        "text": "the Alaska Indians",
        "entity_key": "bhagroup",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " were removed from "
      },
      {
        "text": "the islands",
        "entity_key": "i_chi",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " by "
      },
      {
        "text": "the Government",
        "entity_key": "gov_mexico",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": ". "
      },
      {
        "text": "One \"white Indian woman\"",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " went ashore for "
      },
      {
        "text": "her child",
        "entity_key": "lwchild",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", and was left behind. No attempt was made to rescue her, but sixteen years later "
      },
      {
        "text": "a casual visitor",
        "entity_key": "gni",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": "to "
      },
      {
        "text": "the island",
        "entity_key": "i_sn",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " discovered footprints of "
      },
      {
        "text": "a woman",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": "and evidences of her life. She could not, however, be discovered then or in the following year. "
      },
      {
        "text": "The Catholic Fathers of the 'Old Mission,'",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ],
        "entity_keys": [
          "ndur",
          "jru",
          "aji",
          "sanchez",
          "misfats"
        ],
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " the foremost in every good word and work, offered a reward to any one who would find ",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "the lost woman",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ],
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", and a third effort was made in 1853 [to] discover ",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "the prodigal",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ],
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " about whom there was such a mystery, and in whom the world of ",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "this coast",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ],
        "entity_key": "re_calcoast",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " was beginning to take an interest. Fresh tracks of ",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "the woman",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ],
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " were found. They belonged to very small feet, and were like those that were seen in the first attempt to find ",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "the woman",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ],
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ". Huts made of whale ribs and covered with brush were discovered.",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "At length an object was seen in the distance that appeared to be moving. ",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "Going toward it, they saw ",
        "tropes": [
          4,
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "the woman",
        "tropes": [
          4,
          4
        ],
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " that for eighteen years had reigned ",
        "tropes": [
          4,
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "Queen of San Nicolas",
        "tropes": [
          4,
          4
        ],
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", her subjects being the wild animals, her robe a dress of bird-skins, and her throne the hut she had built. She was seated in an enclosure, so that only her head and shoulders could be seen. Two or three dogs were about her, that disappeared at the command of ",
        "tropes": [
          4,
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "their sovereign",
        "tropes": [
          4,
          4
        ],
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ". She was seated on some grass that covered the ground and served her as a bed. Her dress was neatly made of bird-skins, extending to her ankles, the feathers of which pointed downward. Her head was covered with a thick mat of yellowish-brown hair, and her shoulders were bare. She was occupied in stripping blubber from a piece of sealskin which she held across her knee, and using for that purpose a knife made of an iron hoop. In her hut was a fire, beside which she sat talking to herself, and, occasionally shading her eyes with her hand, looked at ",
        "tropes": [
          4,
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "the men",
        "tropes": [
          4,
          4
        ],
        "entity_keys": [
          "gni",
          "cdi",
          "col",
          "cook",
          "msh",
          "poli",
          "nsk",
          "hva"
        ],
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " that were in search of her.",
        "tropes": [
          4,
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "She received them with much courtesy, bowing and smiling, and showing that ",
        "tropes": [
          4,
          4,
          3
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "this lost child of Nature",
        "tropes": [
          4,
          4,
          3
        ],
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " had much of the politeness of a true woman.",
        "tropes": [
          4,
          4,
          3
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": " She took some roots from the bag, roasted them in the fire, and gave them to ",
        "tropes": [
          4,
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "the men",
        "tropes": [
          4,
          4
        ],
        "entity_keys": [
          "gni",
          "cdi",
          "col",
          "cook",
          "msh",
          "poli",
          "nsk",
          "hva"
        ],
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " to eat.",
        "tropes": [
          4,
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": " She gathered up all her food, which was her chief concern, owing to the famine[s] she had experienced, washed herself at the spring, and followed ",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "the men",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ],
        "entity_keys": [
          "gni",
          "cdi",
          "col",
          "cook",
          "msh",
          "poli",
          "nsk",
          "hva"
        ],
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " cheerfully to ",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "the boat",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ],
        "entity_key": "sh_nidever",
        "entity_type": "ship"
      },
      {
        "text": ".",
        "tropes": [
          4
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": " On being taken to "
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Barbara",
        "entity_key": "ci_sb",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", she manifested great delight on seeing the sights of civilization. She became a universal favorite, and was presented with many gifts. Passengers on "
      },
      {
        "text": "the Panama steamer",
        "entity_key": "sh_panama",
        "entity_type": "ship"
      },
      {
        "text": "that landed there all wanted to see "
      },
      {
        "text": "the lost woman of San Nicolas",
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ". She related by signs her experience on "
      },
      {
        "text": "the island",
        "entity_key": "i_sn",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": ", as she spoke a language that none of "
      },
      {
        "text": "the Spanish fathers",
        "entity_keys": [
          "jru",
          "aji",
          "sanchez",
          "misfats"
        ],
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", versed in Indian dialects, could understand. "
      },
      {
        "text": "Civilization, which prolongs the life of some, shortened that of ",
        "tropes": [
          3
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "the woman of San Nicolas",
        "tropes": [
          3
        ],
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ". An excessive love of fruit led to her death in ",
        "tropes": [
          3
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "Santa Barbara",
        "tropes": [
          3
        ],
        "entity_key": "ci_sb",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " at the age of fifty.",
        "tropes": [
          3
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": " She was buried with the [honors of "
      },
      {
        "text": "the] Catholic Church",
        "entity_key": "ch_catholic",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": "by the "
      },
      {
        "text": "Franciscan Fathers",
        "entity_keys": [
          "jru",
          "aji",
          "sanchez",
          "misfats"
        ],
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": ", and her dress and trinkets were sent to "
      },
      {
        "text": "Rome",
        "entity_key": "ci_rom",
        "entity_type": "place"
      },
      {
        "text": " and placed in "
      },
      {
        "text": "that receptacle of the world's curiosities",
        "entity_key": "mu_vaticanmuseum",
        "entity_type": "org"
      },
      {
        "text": "."
      }
    ],
    [
      {
        "text": "The story of ",
        "tropes": [
          5
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "the lost woman of San Nicolas",
        "tropes": [
          5
        ],
        "entity_key": "lw",
        "entity_type": "person"
      },
      {
        "text": " will always remain a wonderment. Her ingenuity is seen in the pails she made of grass, made to hold water by smearing them with melted asphaltum, and in her bird-skin dresses, her bone needles, her knife of iron hoop, and the language she invented and spoke. It is inexplicable to all who have learned her story, how a woman could live eighteen years on an island, around which the waves were beating a requiem to hope, getting her food and cooking it without even those facilities which are common to the savage, and making her dresses neatly without the aid of needles except what she carved out of bone.",
        "tropes": [
          5
        ]
      },
      {
        "text": "She laid aside one dress for eighteen years, to be worn when the white men should come, of which she had a presentiment. She built her own house, protected herself from the cold, gained supreme control over the wild beasts about her, and preserved her love for men and women for well-nigh two decades of human life alone in the wild. With no previous knowledge of civilization, solitude appeared to have educated her for it. An ordinary woman would have perishe d [sic] with despondency in such a desolate[,] hungry, naked, hopeless outlook.",
        "tropes": [
          1
        ]
      }
    ]
  ]
}